### Callbacks in TypeScript

Callbacks are functions passed as arguments to other functions, to be executed later.

### Typing Callbacks

```typescript
function processData(
  data: number[],
  callback: (item: number) => void
): void {
  data.forEach((item) => callback(item));
}
```

### Callback Type Aliases

```typescript
type ErrorHandler = (error: Error) => void;
type SuccessHandler<T> = (result: T) => void;
type CompletionHandler = () => void;

function fetchData<T>(
  url: string,
  onSuccess: SuccessHandler<T>,
  onError: ErrorHandler,
  onComplete?: CompletionHandler
): void {
  // Implementation
}
```

### Error-First Callbacks

```typescript
type NodeCallback<T> = (error: Error | null, result?: T) => void;

function readFile(
  path: string,
  callback: NodeCallback<string>
): void {
  try {
    const content = "file content";
    callback(null, content);
  } catch (err) {
    callback(err as Error);
  }
}
```

### Callback Hell

Nested callbacks create hard-to-read code. Prefer Promises or async/await:

```typescript
// Avoid deeply nested callbacks
getData((data) => {
  processData(data, (processed) => {
    saveData(processed, (result) => {
      console.log(result);
    });
  });
});
```

> **Key Point:** Always type callback parameters explicitly for better IntelliSense and type safety.

